## Development Workflow

> 📝 See [Senior Developer Guidelines - Implementation Process](.cursor/rules/consistency-senior-dev.mdc#implementation-process) for detailed development steps.

### Git Workflow

> 📝 See [Core Principles - Version Management](mdc:.cursor/rules/core/core-principles.mdc#version-management) for detailed versioning guidelines.

- Use feature branches for all changes
- Branch naming: `feature/<feature-name>`
- Create a pull request for each feature branch
- Review and merge pull requests
- Delete the feature branch after merging
- Use `main` branch for stable releases
- Tag releases with version numbers
- Use semantic versioning (MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH)
- Update `CHANGELOG.md` for each release
- Follow the [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/) specification for commit messages

### Development Steps

1. Create a new feature branch
2. Make changes and commit with descriptive messages
3. Push changes to the feature branch
4. Create a pull request
5. Review and merge the pull request
6. Delete the feature branch
7. Update `CHANGELOG.md` and version number
8. Tag the release with the version number
9. Push the tag to the remote repository

### Versioning Guidelines

- Follow semantic versioning (MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH)
- Increment the MAJOR version for breaking changes
- Increment the MINOR version for new features
- Increment the PATCH version for bug fixes
- Update `CHANGELOG.md` for each release
- Tag releases with version numbers
- Use tags for stable releases and branches for development

### Commit Message Guidelines

- Use the present tense ("Add feature" not "Added feature")
- Use the imperative mood ("Move cursor to..." not "Moves cursor to...")
- Limit the first line to 72 characters or less
- Reference issues and pull requests in the commit message
- Follow the [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/) specification for commit messages

### Pull Request Guidelines

- Use descriptive titles and descriptions
- Reference issues and pull requests in the description
- Include screenshots or GIFs if applicable
- Request reviews from relevant team members
- Address review comments and make changes as needed
- Squash and rebase commits for a clean history
- Delete the feature branch after merging

### Release Guidelines

- Update `CHANGELOG.md` for each release
- Tag releases with version numbers
- Use tags for stable releases and branches for development
- Follow semantic versioning (MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH)
- Increment the MAJOR version for breaking changes
- Increment the MINOR version for new features
- Increment the PATCH version for bug fixes
- Push the tag to the remote repository
- Create a new GitHub release for each tag
- Include release notes in the GitHub release description

